00:02:38.626 --> 00:02:41.330
what can I find out from this
function?

00:02:41.330 --> 00:02:46.574
The first thing is that if you
took the absolute square of this

00:02:46.574 --> 00:02:50.889
function, that is the
probability density to find it

00:02:50.889 --> 00:02:53.090
at the point x.
 

00:02:53.090 --> 00:02:56.667
By that I mean if you multiply
both by some infinitesimal

00:02:56.667 --> 00:03:00.245
Δx that is the
probability that the particle

00:03:00.245 --> 00:03:03.120
will be between x and
x dx.

00:03:03.120 --> 00:03:05.188
That means that you take this
ψ and you square it.

00:03:05.188 --> 00:03:08.544
So you will get something that
will go to 0 here,

00:03:08.544 --> 00:03:11.620
go up, go to zero,
do something like that.

00:03:11.620 --> 00:03:15.662
This is ψ^(2),
and that's your probability

00:03:15.662 --> 00:03:18.840
density and what we mean by
density is,

00:03:18.840 --> 00:03:23.647
if the function p(x) has
an area with the x-axis

00:03:23.647 --> 00:03:28.300
like p(x)dx that's the
